{
  "doc_id": "56187",
  "text": "Studies show that females bred by artificial insemination receive a premium [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Females that will calve within a short span receive a premium [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Synchronized AI heifers receive a premium of $25 to $80 per head [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . [CITATION_8] found that buyers are willing to pay a higher premium for pens of heifers bred to the same sire. A heifer that is bred to an Angus sire will sell at a price premium [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . A heifer's weight influences price [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . Weight is normally expressed in a quadratic or squared weight term. However, [CITATION_13] found a linear relationship between weight and price based on the need for heifers to qualify for the program. [CITATION_14] did not find discounts for higher birth weights because some service sire breeds had a maximum allowed (within the breed) birth weight EPD program requirement. [CITATION_15] found that calf carcass characteristics such as carcass weight, marbling, and ribeye area are also significant in explaining price. This study specified marbling and milk in a logarithmic form so lower scores were discounted.",
